<!-- External Metadata URL: cocoon://metadata/handle/123456789/94/mets.xml?rightsMDTypes=METSRIGHTS-->
<div xmlns:oreatom="http://www.openarchives.org/ore/atom/" xmlns:ore="http://www.openarchives.org/ore/terms/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" class="item-summary-view-metadata">
<h1>Young children expressing their identity through the arts</h1>
<p class="author-item-view">
<a href="/xmlui/browse?value=Binder, Marni&amp;type=author&#10;            &#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;">Binder, Marni</a>
</p>
<h2>Citation</h2>Binder, M., &amp; Kotsopoulos, S. (2011). Multimodal literacy narratives: Weaving the threads of young children’s identity through the arts. Journal of Research in Childhood Education, 25(4), 339-363. <a href="http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02568543.2011.606762#.Um6EaRDjXMY">(link to study)
            							</a>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Insights</h2>
<div>
<p>Young children can use multiple types of art in addition to writing in order to describe their personal thoughts and experiences.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Practice insights</h2>
<div>
<ul>
<li>Educators need to provide young children with opportunities and experiences to share their thoughts with others and to explore how they think about themselves in relation to the world.&#13;<li />Educators need to provide young children with the opportunity to use art as an alternate form of literacy expression.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Background/Rationale of the paper</h2>
<div>
<p>This paper describes the processes in which junior and senior kindergarten children used multiple forms of art to represent who they were and what was important in their world.  The researchers worked with a group of 12 young children over nine weeks. Each two-hour session included a storybook reading, and involved a process and series of art activities that led to the making of a quilt square. At the end of the nine-week period, the children created a community quilt and “me” poems.  The study’s data consisted of the children’s quilt squares, drawings, a community quilt, the children’s poetry, recorded discussions with the children and teachers, videotapes of the sessions as well as the teachers’ and researchers’ journal notes.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Summary</h2>
<div>
<p>Each session was part of an overall process and each step of the process was considered important. During each session, the children recalled what they had discussed and done in the previous week, and what they had learned from it. Children used the concept of process to describe what they were doing (e.g., “step by step”).  As part of this process, the researchers saw a shift in the children from focusing on what was important to them as individuals to things that were important to the group. The children began to show appreciation for and interest in other children’s drawings and artifacts. Creating the group quilt out of individual quilt squares was an experience that built empathy in the children, and strengthened the children’s relationships with one another and their teachers.  The weekly opportunities to tell their stories, listen to stories, and to each other empowered the children to become more able to speak about their thoughts.  As the sessions progressed, the children learned that they could use alternative ways of communicating, such as expressing concepts and ideas through drawings or paintings instead of only relying upon words.</p>
</div>
</div>
<h2>Contact the Ryerson researcher(s)</h2>Marni Binder, Associate Professor, Early Childhood Studies <a href="&#10;            &#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;mailto:mbinder@ryerson.ca">(email)
            								</a>
